{{Infobox academic|name=Aryn Martin|residence=Canada, United States|nationality=Canadian|occupation=sociologist, historian, professor, university administrator|education=Queen's University, York University, Cornell University|influences=Michael Lynch, Donna Haraway, Harry Collins, Natasha Myers, Hannah Landecker|discipline=sociology of science, science and technology studies|workplaces=York University|influenced=Natasha Myers, Michael Lynch|principal_ideas=feminist understanding of microchimerism and identity, politics of care in technoscience}}
'''Aryn Martin''' is a sociologist, and historian of biomedicine, as well as a scholar of feminist science and technology studies at [[York University]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://profiles.laps.yorku.ca/profiles/aryn/|title=aryn {{!}} Faculty of Liberal Arts & Professional Studies|website=profiles.laps.yorku.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref> where she is an associate professor of sociology. She is affiliated with the graduate programs in social, political, science, technology, and environmental studies. She received her [[Bachelor of Science]] in biology at [[Queen's University]], a [[master's degree]] in environmental studies at [[York University]],<ref name=":0" /> and a PhD in science and technology studies at [[Cornell University]], under the supervision of [[Michael Lynch (ethnomethodologist)|Michael Lynch]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/i-contain-multitudes-chimeras-cells-and-the-materialization-of-identities/oclc/864102986&referer=brief_results|title="I contain multitudes": Chimeras, cells and the materialization of identities.|last=Martin|first=Aryn|date=2006|isbn=9780542780110|language=English}}</ref> Her work is on feminist theories of the body and biology, especially the implications for identity surrounding the phenomenon of fetomaternal [[microchimerism]] and other forms of [[Chimera (genetics)|genetic chimeras]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theoryculturesociety.org/interview-with-aryn-martin-on-microchimerism/|title=Interview with Aryn Martin on Microchimerism - Theory, Culture & Society|date=2010-11-10|work=Theory, Culture & Society|access-date=2018-10-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alfred|first=Tauber,|date=2002-05-21|title=The Biological Notion of Self and Non-self|url=https://stanford.library.sydney.edu.au/archives/win2012/entries/biology-self/|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shildrick|first=Margrit|date=2013|title=Re-imagining Embodiment: Prostheses, Supplements and Boundaries|journal=Somatechnics|language=en|volume=3|issue=2|pages=270–286|doi=10.3366/soma.2013.0098|issn=2044-0138}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pictorial.jezebel.com/one-person-two-sets-of-dna-the-strange-case-of-the-hu-1689290862|title=One Person, Two Sets of DNA: The Strange Case of the Human Chimera|last=Edwards|first=Stassa|work=Pictorial|access-date=2018-10-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://w3.stu.ca/stu/events/102527|title=Annual STS Lecture: Dr. Aryn Martin Delivers|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://binocular2018.wordpress.com/2018-keynote-address/|title=Keynote|date=2018-04-25|work=2018 Binocular Conference|access-date=2018-10-12|language=en-US}}</ref>. Her dissertation on the history of human chimeras was funded by the [[National Science Foundation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0432120|title=NSF Award Search: Award#0432120 - Dissertation Research: "I contain multitudes": Genetic chimeras and material negotiations of identity|website=www.nsf.gov|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>
In 2017, Martin became the Associate Dean of Students at York University's Faculty of Graduate Studies.
